2024 Spatial Hackathon Vignette: Image Processing Tools

Set-up

This vignette reflects some of our stretch goals for this Hackathon. Given neighbourhood identification in our previous vignettes, we wondered if it would be possible to integrate our neighbourhoods with H&E information (Aim 2 of this Hackathon). To that end, we developed some functions for image processing.

## Dependencies for image processing

Preliminary image analysis (incomplete)

In the time given, we were able to achieve the following:

  1. Stain deconvolution 2. Image gridding and unbiased clustering of Fourier transform spaces

We were unable, in the time allotted, figure out the translation of H&E image coordinates with that of the Xenium-derived cellular coordinates. We thus resorted to griding.

Stain deconvolution

We read images using the RBioFormats package, and quickly plot with the imager package. This allows us to load in a lower resolution without straining our resources.

Given a H&E image, one early pre-processing step is to separate the image into its H and E components. This is quickly achievable with matrix deconvolution.

Entropy is calculated by comparing H and E matrices.

heList <- heDeconvolve(ima$im)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(as.cimg(ima$im))
Warning: Assuming third dimension corresponds to colour
for(i in 1:length(heList)){
  plot(as.cimg(heList[[i]]), main=names(heList)[i])
}
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
